                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Challenges on All Sides for the Fed</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-08-31T10:58:14+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 31, 2015 6:58 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 31, 2015 6:58 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/morning-agenda-challenges-on-all-sides-for-the-fed/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Challenges on All Sides for the Fed" data-description="Bitcoin Disrupts Wall Street | Daniel Zwirn&#039;s New Partnership | Puerto Rico Postpones Debt Plan">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CHALLENGES ON ALL SIDES FOR THE FED</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Federal Reserveâs vice chairman, Stanley Fischer, said he expected inflation to rebound to a healthier pace and maintained that the Fed was   <b>still on course to raise interest rates this year</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/30/business/optimistic-about-inflation-stanley-fischer-suggests-that-fed-will-stick-to-plan-on-rates.html?ref=dealbook">Binyamin Appelbaum reports in The New York Times</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Fischer, whose comments were closely watched after days of market turmoil, reiterated that  <b>economic conditions in the United States are approaching the standards the Fed deems necessary</b>  for it to raise rates. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fed said after its July meeting that it  <b>wanted to see further improvement in the labor market</b>. The Labor Department released data showing the economy had added about 215,000 jobs in July. Mr. Fischer said the Fed was awaiting the result of the August survey, but emphasized that he could not say what decision would be reached in September. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He was speaking from the annual policy retreat in Jackson Hole, Wyo., where Fed officials were facing  <b>pressure from both the left and right over interest rates</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/business/challenged-on-left-and-right-the-fed-faces-a-decision-on-rates.html">Mr. Appelbaum reports</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fedâs plans have become a point of contention in  <b>a broader debate about the governmentâs management of the American economy</b>. Liberals see a need for more aggressive measures to bolster growth, but conservatives are worried that Washington and the Fed are already intervening too much. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is also   <b>debate over the goal of moderating inflation</b>. Liberals say the Fed should have broader goals like lowering employment and raising living standards. Conservatives want to focus on inflation by requiring officials to follow rules in making policy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The debate has been affected by the fact that  <b>inflation in recent years has not behaved as economists predicted</b>. The basic paradigm, known as the Phillips Curve, is that inflation falls as unemployment rises, and rises when it falls. But inflation did not fall as much as expected during the Great Recession and has remained surprisingly weak during the recovery. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Central bankers, however, maintain that  <b>the basic understanding of inflation remains more functional than alternatives</b>, if imperfect. Mr. Fischer said that his confidence in an eventual rebound in inflation remained âpretty high.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BITCOIN DISRUPTS WALL STREET </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Far from its reputation as a virtual currency used by drug dealers and shadowy hackers, Bitcoin is starting to be viewed a disruptive force in industries ranging from accounting to music. But the biggest spenders on Bitcoin technology are on Wall Street â <b>the very industry that Bitcoin was created to circumvent</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/business/dealbook/bitcoin-technology-piques-interest-on-wall-st.html?ref=dealbook">as DealBookâs Nathaniel Popper reports</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For those in the finance industry, Bitcoin isnât just a digital token for online purchases. They are not interested in selling or owning the virtual currency. Many believe that the software that the currency runs on will allow people and banks to directly exchange money and assets like stocks and bonds  <b>without having to rely on a long chain of expensive middlemen</b>.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Until now, digital transactions have always gone through a central authority that can move the money and update records on both sides, as PayPal and Visa do for online purchases. The Bitcoin network is decentralized and comprises users who jointly keep track of transactions, updating in real time with no single user or company in charge.  <b>All transactions are recorded on a public ledger known as the blockchain that, so far, has proved impossible to tamper with.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks are  <b>looking at whether blockchain technology can be used independently</b>, without the virtual currency it was first used for. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At most banks,  <b>the activity has been going on behind the scenes</b>. Executives from more than a dozen large banks gathered at Bank of America in April to confidentially discuss how Bitcoin could be used to change foreign currency trading, the largest financial market  in the world. Central banks like the Federal Reserve and the Bank of England have their own teams looking at the technology. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banks like Goldman Sachs, Santander and BBVA have made investments in start-ups working on Bitcoin technology. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The most intense work is being done by financial companies like the Nasdaq OMX Group, which has several programmers in Manhattan  <b>preparing software to roll out this year</b>. The new software will allow the trading of stocks in private companies, like tech start-ups, on a new kind of blockchain. This would replace the current system of paper certification, which can take weeks.<br />
Nasdaq is also looking at using the blockchain in other markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âA year ago, it was more of an idea,â said Max Neukirchen, the head of corporate strategy at JPMorgan Chase. âNow, it is a real opportunity. You test it and realize that  <b>this can play a big role in our thinking about how our own infrastructure will evolve.â</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The currency has  <b>come a long way from the derision</b>  that many, including JPMorganâs chief executive, Jamie Dimon, expressed in 2013 when it burst into the public consciousness.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nonetheless, there is still debate about where the technology is likely to be put into real-world use. At Barclays, some of the 20 internal experiments are looking at ways to  <b>use the blockchain to speed up and lower the cost of consumer payments.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But bankers say the research is generally aimed at changing the   <b>systems used to buy and sell sophisticated assets like syndicated loans and corporate bonds.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It may seem like a rather esoteric business, but  <b>huge amounts of money are turned over each day in these markets</b> and they can influence the profits of the largest financial institutions. More than $3 trillion changes hands each day in the foreign currency market.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>DANIEL ZWIRNâS NEW PARTNERSHIP</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The hedge fund manager Daniel B. Zwirn closed his firm, D.B. Zwirn in 2009 amid a Securities and Exchange Commission investigation into accounting irregularities. Now he is  <b>trying his luck again with the backing of a big investor</b>,  <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/31/business/dealbook/daniel-zwirn-forges-partnership-with-canadian-investment-firm.html?ref=dealbook">Alexandra Stevenson reports in DealBook</a>. Mr. Zwirn has teamed up with Westaim Corporation, a Canadian investment company, to create Arena Finance Company and Arena Investors, according to people briefed on the matter. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Arena Finance will  begin with roughly $183 million and will buy and create commercial and real estate loans. The aim is  <b>to go where banks are not willing to venture</b>, like loans to small-scale oil and gas companies and subprime auto lending. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Arena Investors has about $15 million of Mr. Zwirnâs family money and will invest money on behalf of institutional investors, including insurance companies. It will look for  opportunities to lend to  <b>companies that need cash or investors in distressed situations</b>  who want an easy exit. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This will be the first time since D.B. Zwirn that Mr. Zwirn has managed money for outside investors. D.B. Zwirn was upended after the firm  <b>uncovered a series of accounting irregularities in late 2006</b>, including $3.8 million taken from investors to help finance the purchase of an $18 million Gulfstream IV private jet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2011, after several years of investigation, <b>the S.E.C. sued Perry Gruss, the chief financial officer</b>, contending that he âknowingly misusedâ $870 million in clientsâ funds â including for the Gulfstream IV. The original discovery and subsequent investigation set off lawsuits between Mr. Zwirn and Mr. Gruss, and investors and D.B. Zwirn.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Westaim is expected to announce the news on Monday.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
